        answer: 'New Jersey leads nationally in multiple specialty crops with impressive rankings and production values. The state ranks #5 nationally for blueberries producing 50.2 million pounds valued at $92.1 million (primarily Atlantic County/Hammonton "Blueberry Capital"), #3 for cranberries with 580,000 barrels expected in 2024 valued at $19.9 million (Pine Barrens bogs in Burlington/Atlantic/Ocean counties), #3 for potted flowering plants ($77.5 million), #5 for nursery stock ($296 million), and #4 for peaches ($18.9 million, July-September harvest). Additional Top 10 national crops include tomatoes ($47.3 million), bell peppers ($36.05 million), sweet corn ($26.7 million), cucumbers ($12.4 million), spinach ($4.9 million, #3-4 nationally), eggplant, squash, asparagus, and snap beans. The greenhouse/nursery/floriculture/sod sector dominates at $725 million total (largest agricultural sector, #9 nationally). Specialty items where NJ ranks Top 10 nationally include plums, bok choy, escarole, kale, romaine lettuce, and fresh-cut herbs (Atlantic County #6 nationally). The state produces 1+ million bushels of apples annually (40+ varieties), operates 30+ shellfish aquaculture farms (#5 nationally for hard clams, $7.2+ million sales), and supports 75 wineries across 1,082 vineyard acres with Cape May soils compared to Bordeaux, France.',
